    <item>
      <title>QIF Graphics</title>
      <link>https://ramongonze.github.io/project/qif-graphics/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 02 Jul 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ramongonze.github.io/project/qif-graphics/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Graphical tool for representing the Quantitative Information Flow (QIF) among a set of three secrets. Developed in C/C++ all the graphic structures were made using &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.raylib.com/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;raylib&lt;/a&gt; library and &lt;a href=&#34;https://emscripten.org/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;emscripten&lt;/a&gt; to compile the project to WebAssembly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The tool is available &lt;a href=&#34;https://homepages.dcc.ufmg.br/~ramon.gonze/qif-graphics&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>QIF Library</title>
      <link>https://ramongonze.github.io/project/qif-library/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 02 Jul 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ramongonze.github.io/project/qif-library/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Python library for Quantitative Information Flow (QIF). This library models the basics of QIF such as secrets, channels, and the g-vulnerability framework.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
